    code: "MH701",
    title: "BSc General Nursing",
    description: "Our innovative programme integrates theory, skills practise and practice placements. It aims to prepare competent graduates who are confident in their ability to deliver person centred, safe, compassionate, evidence-based, effective and high-quality care across diverse healthcare settings. Our School’s goal is that on completion of the programme our nursing graduates are flexible and adaptable, capable of working in rapidly changing healthcare contexts and settings, critical thinkers and future leaders with capacity to effect change to positively benefit patient care and health care. MU nursin",
    fullSummary: "Our innovative programme integrates theory, skills practise and practice placements. It aims to prepare competent graduates who are confident in their ability to deliver person centred, safe, compassionate, evidence-based, effective and high-quality care across diverse healthcare settings. Our School’s goal is that on completion of the programme our nursing graduates are flexible and adaptable, capable of working in rapidly changing healthcare contexts and settings, critical thinkers and future leaders with capacity to effect change to positively benefit patient care and health care. MU nursing students will: Complete a cutting-edge programme designed to meet Ireland’s growing population and changing healthcare requirements. Be taught by experienced educators and health professionals who work across a variety of healthcare disciplines, settings and research fields. Take a programme that actively promotes person-centredness and prioritises clinical excellence using innovative learning and teaching approaches. Gain hands-on practice experience across a diverse range of community and hospital clinical settings. Learn in a state-of-the-art learning environment with access to a comprehensive range of academic and personal resources to support their learning. Complete a degree that will prepare them to work in a variety of practice settings, including hospital and integrated care settings. Successful completion of the degree programme leads to eligibility to register as a general nurse with the Nursing and Midwifery Board of Ireland. Registered General Nurses have wide-ranging employment opportunities in Ireland, across the EU and beyond. Most graduates opt to consolidate their learning by working as a staff nurse in a hospital or community setting. Many go on to complete further studies in their chosen specialism, for example, community, emergency or palliative care nursing. There are also opportunities to work in different care settings within and outside the HSE, including charities such as Enable Ireland, Simon and many others. With experience and further study, opportunities for advancement include advanced nurse practitioner, clinical nurse specialist, nursing management or nursing education.",
